verbs.description: interleave (third-person singular simple present interleaves, present participle interleaving, simple past and past participle interleaved)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To insert (pages, which are normally blank) between the pages of a book.
examples: Let a Servitor transcribe the quotations, and interleave them with references to save time. This will shorten the work and lessen the fatigue.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To intersperse (something) at regular intervals between the parts of a thing or between items in a group.
examples: I had the demon’s own time with my armor, and this delayed me a little.  It is troublesome to get into, and there is so much detail.  First you wrap a layer or two of blanket around your body,  […]  then you put on your sleeves and shirt of chain mail—  […]  then you put on your shoes—flat-boats roofed over with interleaving bands of steel—and screw your clumsy spurs into the heels.

entries.meaning: (computing, transitive) To allocate (things such as successive segments of memory) to different tasks.
